2) Embedding Model

In our experiment, we need an embedding model to calculate the vectors of every CoT steps. we choose the bge-m3 [29] model who is supported by the BAAI company, and it supports vector calculations in multiple languages and input texts with a maximum length of 8192, which is suitable for our task. It is also worth mentioning that texts’ vector calculation technology has developed to a relatively mature stage, we can also use other vector models to conduct vector calculations for the CoT steps.

3) Supervised Finetuning for Llm’s CoT Inferring

The output of traditional large models usually directly gives the answers to the questions, in addition to directly adding prompts that guide the output of CoT to the end of the prompt, for example, “let’s verify step by step”. In order to guide large language models to output the CoT reasoning process that we need, we can also further fine-tune the LLMs. As illustrated in the Figure 4, We need to build a dataset containing “thoughts” to further fine-tune the model. In this way, the model can deliberately think during the reasoning process and output the thinking behind the problem. In our experiment, we select the OpenO1-SFT [30] dataset who contains about 77.7k rows of data. And for models’ training part, we use the LLaMa-Factory [31] framework as our training framework, we trained each model 3 epochs on
